{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510250","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510250"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:26:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:26:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11510"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11510","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11510"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.87,0.05,0.03,0.03,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4141"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78806"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4141","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4141"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11510"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64155"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1243"},{"type":"tags","id":"6132"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5200"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5242"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26985"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27011"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78806","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78806"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 44-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a one-week history of right shoulder pain. He reports that the pain is reproduced during a game of rugby when he lifts both hands overhead to catch the ball. This sharp pain tends to worsen with repetition of overhead activity and lasts four to six hours after the game. He usually takes ibuprofen to relieve the pain, but now the pain persists throughout the night, and he finds difficulty sleeping on his right side. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. A shoulder examination reveals a positive empty can test. The examiner diagnoses the patient with a rotator cuff injury.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following muscles is most likely to be torn?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Supraspinatus","Deltoid","Subscapularis","Infraspinatus","Teres minor"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe positive empty can test is a clinical manoeuvre used to assess the integrity of the \u003Cstrong\u003Esupraspinatus\u003C/strong\u003E muscle, which is part of the rotator cuff. This test involves the patient elevating their arm to 90\u00b0 in the scapular plane with full internal rotation (thumb pointing down) and resisting downward pressure. Pain or weakness during this test suggests a tear or tendinopathy of the supraspinatus muscle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Einfraspinatus\u003C/strong\u003E muscle is another component of the rotator cuff, primarily responsible for external rotation of the shoulder. It is not typically assessed by the empty can test.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esubscapularis\u003C/strong\u003E muscle is responsible for internal rotation of the shoulder and is not evaluated by the empty can test. Tests such as the lift-off test are used to assess subscapularis function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eteres minor\u003C/strong\u003E muscle, like the infraspinatus, is involved in external rotation and is not assessed by the empty can test.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Edeltoid\u003C/strong\u003E muscle is responsible for shoulder abduction and is not part of the rotator cuff. It is not evaluated by the empty can test.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pain during downward resistance against the patient\u2019s affected arm at 90\u00b0 elevation in the scapular plane and full internal rotation is known as a positive \u0027empty can\u0027 test, indicating a supraspinatus muscle injury.","The supraspinatus muscle is commonly involved in rotator cuff injuries, especially in individuals engaging in repetitive overhead activities."],"references":["Yamamoto A, Takagishi K, Kobayashi T, Shitara H, Ichinose T, Takasawa E, Shimoyama D, Osawa T. The impact of faulty posture on rotator cuff tears with and without symptoms. J Shoulder Elbow Surg. 2015 Mar;24(3):446-52. doi: 10.1016/j.jse.2014.07.012. Epub 2014 Oct 16. PMID: 25441565. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25441565/","Leong HT, Fu SC, He X, Oh JH, Yamamoto N, Hang S. Risk factors for rotator cuff tendinopathy: A systematic review and meta-analysis. J Rehabil Med. 2019 Oct 4;51(9):627-637. doi: 10.2340/16501977-2598. PMID: 31489438. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31489438/","May T, Garmel GM. Rotator Cuff Injury. [Updated 2023 Jun 26]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK547664/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64155"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11510"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64155","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64155"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-12T19:02:56+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-22T08:32:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4141"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78806"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"rel